Loading data and relevant libraries

First, Ill load the tidyverse library and my dataset. As a reminder, my dataset is filtered for older adults (65+) in Massachusetts. Ill also exclude folks whose total incomes are $0 or less for the purpose of analyses.

library (tidyverse)
library(jtools)
library(interactions)
library(knitr)

person_data <- read_csv("people.csv")
attach(person_data)

person_data_recode <- person_data %>%
  filter (PINCP > 0)

Regression models

Model 1: Initial regression model

In assignment 4, I used age, household size, sex, independent living difficulty, and housing tenure to predict total income. For this assignment, Im going to alter the model and the dependent variable be age, and have total income an independent variable. I found that the previous model was simple and not very informative. I wonder what it might look like if I make age the dependent variable, and make income an independent variable, along with the other independent variables: household size, sex, independent living difficulty, and housing tenure.

As stated earlier, this model also excludes folks whose total incomes are $0 or less (which the model in Assignment 4 included).

model1 <- lm(AGEP ~ PINCP + NP + SEX_label + DOUT_label + TEN_label,
            data = person_data_recode)

Model 2: Converting a continuous variable to a categorical varaible

Im curious if there is less of a linear effect with income than how Ive been thinking about it. Ill convert income from a continuous to categorical variable, referring to the interquartile range to mutate the variable into categories.

person_data_recode <- person_data_recode %>%
  mutate (DC_PINCP = case_when(PINCP  < 14092.5 ~ "Less than $14,092.50",
                           PINCP  >= 14092.5 & PINCP <27000.0 ~ "$14,092.50 to $27,000",
                           PINCP  >= 27000.0 & PINCP <54040.0 ~ "$27,000 to $54,040",
                           PINCP >= 54040.0 ~ "$54,040 or more"))

model2 <- lm(AGEP ~ DC_PINCP + NP + SEX_label + DOUT_label + TEN_label,
            data = person_data_recode)

Model 4: Adding an interaction term

Lastly, Ill see what effect independent living difficulty has on all of the other relationships within the initial model.

model4 <- lm(AGEP ~ PINCP + NP + SEX_label + DOUT_label + TEN_label +
PINCP:DOUT_label + NP:DOUT_label + SEX_label:DOUT_label + TEN_label:DOUT_label,
            data = person_data_recode)

Visualizing model fit differences

ModelFit <- tibble(model = c(1, 2, 3, 4),
                   R_square = c(summary(model1)$adj.r.squared,
                                summary(model2)$adj.r.squared,
                                summary(model3)$adj.r.squared,
                                summary(model4)$adj.r.squared))

ggplot(ModelFit, aes(x = model, y = R_square)) +
  geom_line() +
  scale_x_continuous(name = "",
                   breaks = breaks <- seq(1, 4, by = 1),
                   labels = paste("Model", breaks)) +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Adjusted R-squared value") +
  theme_bw()

Here we clearly see that Model 4 is the best fitting model, although the difference is small (less than 2% better than the initial model).
